Graphical Methods for Describing Data

Categorical Variable

  • Bar chart

  • Pie chart

Quantitative Variable

  • Histogram

  • Stem-and-Leaf plot

  • Box plot

Blood Type A phlebotomist draws the blood of a random sample of 50 patients and determines their blood types as shown: A, B, AB, O, AB, O, O, O, O, O, O, O, B, O, O, A, A, B, O, A, A, B, A, A, A, A, O, A, O, O, A, A, B, A, B, O, AB, A, A, A, O, O, AB, O, A, A, A, O, O, O \(\phantom{Sullivan, ex2.24, p.73}\)

a) Construct a frequency distribution.

b) Construct a relative frequency distribution.

  • Step 1: Identify the type of data. (Categorical)

  • Step 2: Make a frequency table. (Count occurrence of each blood type in data)

  • Step 3: Compute the relative frequency for each group. \((\frac{freq}{total})\)

Blood Type Frequency Rel. Frequency
A 18 0.36
AB 4 0.08
B 6 0.12
O 22 0.44

  • The frequency distribution lists each category of data, and the “number of occurrences” for each category of data.

  • The relative frequency for a particular category is the “proportion” of the observations that belong to that category. Rel. Freq. = \(\frac{freq}{total}\)

c) According to the data, which blood type is most common?

  • Type O

d) According to the data, which blood type is the least common?

  • Type AB

e) Use the results of the sample to conjecture the percentage of the population that has type O blood. Is this an example of descriptive or inferential statistics?

  • 44% of the population has type O blood.

  • This example is inferential because we use 44% (a statistic) to estimate the true percentage of people in the population with type O blood.

Bar Chart

  • The bar chart displays the frequency distribution of categorical data.

  • Each category in the frequency distribution is represented by a bar or rectangle.

  • The height of the bar represents the frequency (or relative frequency) for each category.

  • In the bar chart, make sure the vertical axis starts at “zero”, the bars have same width and color, and all axes are labeled.

  • The Pareto chart is a bar graph whose bars are drawn in decreasing order of frequency or relative frequency.

Pie Chart

A pie chart is a circle divided into sectors. Each sector represents a category of data. The area of each sector is proportional to the frequency of the category.

Steps for creating a histogram

1) Sort the data in ascending order.

2) Define the interval classes (bins).

  • In this example, I would like to make a histogram with 7 bins (optional).

  • Identify the minimum and maximum. In this example, min=6.12 and max=25.33

  • Since you need to include the minimum and maximum, let’s start the histogram at 6 and end at 27 (optional).

  • The intervals’ width is \(\frac{27 - 6}{7}\) = 3

  • Interval classes: \([6, 9), [9, 12), [12, 15), [15, 18), [18, 21), [21, 24), [24, 27)\)

3) Count (frequency) the numerical data that fall in each interval.

4) For relative frequency histogram, use the same interval classes, but compute the proportion for each class.

Class Frequency Relative Frequency
[6, 9) 25 25/51 = 0.49
[9, 12) 12 12/51 = 0.23
[12, 15) 9 9/51 = 0.18
[15, 18) 4 4/51 = 0.08
[18, 21) 0 0/51 = 0
[21, 24) 0 0/51 = 0
[24, 27] 1 1/51 = 0.02

Description of the Histogram

Main characteristics: Shape and number of modes.

  • The shape of the histogram is classified typically as symmetric, left (or negatively) skewed, or right (or positively) skewed.

  • The skeweness is determined by the side (left or right) of the long tail in the histogram.

  • Symmetric distribution splits the histogram (dot plot or stem-and-leaf plot) down the middle, the right and the left sides are mirror images.

  • Modes refers to the peaks in the distribution.

  • An unimodal histogram has a single peak. A Bimodal has two peaks, and a multimodal has more than two peaks.

Bimodal Distribution

Uniform (All classes have the same frequency - Fair die)

Symmetric bell-shape, unimodal. Highest frequency occurs in the middle.

Positively skewed (or right skewed. The upper tail of the histogram stretches out much farther than the lower tail), unimodal

Negatively skewed (or left skewed. The lower tail is much longer than the upper tail), unimodal

Stem-and-Leaf Plot

Stem plots or Stem-and-Leaf plots are a simple way to display small data sets of quantitative type.

In a stem-and-leaf plot, the rightmost digit is the leaf, and the remaining digits from the stem. For example, if a data value is 14, then 1 is the stem and 4 the leaf.

For example, consider the following data:

 [1] 21.0 21.0 22.8 21.4 18.7 18.1 14.3 24.4 22.8 19.2 17.8 16.4 17.3 15.2 10.4
[16] 10.4 14.7 32.4 30.4 33.9 21.5 15.5 15.2 13.3 19.2 27.3 26.0 30.4 15.8 19.7
[31] 15.0 21.4

Some Observations:

  • The first stem and leaf, 10|44, indicates two data values: 10.4 and 10.4. The minimum is 10.4. It is a coincidence that two cars have the same mpg. Similarly, the last stem, 33|9, represents the maximum data value 33.9.

  • Similar to the histogram, the stem-and-leaf plot displays the distribution of a quantitative data, with the difference that you can visualize now each data value and identify the minimum and maximum.

  • In this version of stem-and-leaf plot, you can identify the location of the median. The numbers on the left column to the stem indicate the data count. The one in parenthesis (3) show the location of the median in that particular stem.

  • The stem-and-leaf plot can also reveal skewness, modes and range.
